aws::graph::propositions: # Aviation Accident in Wasilla, Alaska on September 30, 2013
The accident occurred in Wasilla, Alaska.
The accident occurred on September 30, 2013, at 08:00 Local time.
The aircraft involved was a Piper PA 18-150.
The aircraft registration was N40579.
The defining event of the accident was structural icing.
The flight was conducted under Part 91: General aviation - Personal.
The accident number was ANC13CA107.
The aircraft sustained substantial damage.
There was 1 person involved in the accident.
No injuries occurred in the accident.
The pilot attempted to takeoff from a public street.
The airplane would not climb during takeoff.
The airplane struck a light pole.
The airplane sustained substantial damage to both wings.
The airplane sustained substantial damage to the fuselage.
The pilot failed to remove heavy frost from the airplane prior to the takeoff attempt.
There were no preaccident mechanical malfunctions in the airplane.
There were no preaccident mechanical failures in the airplane that would have precluded normal operation.
The National Transportation Safety Board determined the probable cause of the accident.
The probable cause of the accident was the pilot's improper preflight inspection.
The probable cause of the accident was the pilot's failure to remove heavy frost from the airplane prior to attempting a takeoff.
Personnel issues included preflight inspection by the pilot.
Personnel issues included lack of action by the pilot.
Environmental issues included conditions conducive to structural icing.
Environmental issues included a pole that contributed to the accident outcome.

text:
# Aviation Investigation Final Report

## Location:
Wasilla, Alaska

## Date & Time: 
September 30, 2013, 08:00 Local

## Aircraft:
Piper PA 18-150

## Defining Event:
Structural icing

## Flight Conducted Under:
Part 91: General aviation - Personal

## Accident Number:
ANC13CA107

## Registration:
N40579

## Aircraft Damage:
Substantial

## Injuries:
1 None

## Analysis
The pilot was attempting to takeoff from a public street, but the airplane would not climb, and struck a light pole, sustaining substantial damage to both wings and the fuselage. The pilot stated that he failed to remove heavy frost from the airplane prior to the takeoff attempt. He also stated that there were no preaccident mechanical malfunctions or failures that would have precluded normal operation.

## Probable Cause and Findings
The National Transportation Safety Board determines the probable cause(s) of this accident to be:The pilot's improper preflight inspection, and failure to remove heavy frost from the airplane prior to attempting a takeoff.

## Findings

| | |
|-|-|
| Personnel issues | Preflight inspection - Pilot |
| Personnel issues | Lack of action - Pilot |
| Environmental issues | Conducive to structural icing - Decision related to condition |
| Environmental issues | Pole - Contributed to outcome |
